This is a novel exercise to help enhance shoulder stability when lifting overhead - something I first learned from @benlustigphysiotherapy. I’ve used it many times in the past half year with patients of mine recovering from shoulder pain who need more stability when lifting overhead and have seen tremendous improvements. 
.
When to use: be sure to try the test I showed in this video first!!!! If you’re weak - then try & retest to see if this is helpful for you. Remember, “corrective exercises” are only helpful if used in the right situation. Never do an exercise just because it looks cool on social media.😉
.
Shout out to @benlustigphysiotherapy for sharing this exercise with me & @edpilgrimdpt for being my model athlete today. Also shout out to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body & @olychad for his lifting demos.

node.text:
During Luke’s injury rehab with me, we ran into a pretty significant limitation in ankle mobility. Now we were definitely seeing some progress with banded joint mobilizations, stretching and soft tissue work with rolling, but he was still a little off balance in his bottom squat position.📝
.
Now when I see problems like this – we often look at the ankle joint  especially the motion of knee moving over the toe – a motion called dorsiflexion – but we need to also look at the motions that occur in other planes like rotation and glide.✅
.
I assessed his lateral shin motion with this movement. Clearly very different on his injury side. This prompted me to test his tibial rotation and as you can see he has much less rotation on his injured side.📝
.
I suggested he use this banded drill. With the band placed under the base of his 1st toe, he tensioned the band and drove his knee out to the side – feeling his glutes working hard and held for 10”. Now if you don’t keep a stable foot during this motion the band will snap out from under your foot.❌ .
We also worked on trying to improve lateral tibial glide, holding the foot down in place and pushing the knee to the side and holding for a few seconds. After performing those you can see a huge difference in ankle mobility.🙌🏼 .
So the next week when we were squatting, I noted he was a little off balance in his bottom position – with the bar shooting out over his toes. We did one more set of tibial rotation drills and the very next see you can see a large difference – now more balanced and able to sit down with the bar over his mid foot.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @thelukemeredith for putting in the hard work during rehab, you're doing such great work man. Also thank you to @3d4medical with the compete anatomy app for the visual of the body today. .

Dr. Stuart McGill @backfitpro is the foremost authority in the world on back mechanics. He has spent his career studying the spine & the mechanics behind injury. There’s unfortunately a growing body of critics who arrogantly dismiss his work by citing a few articles. In this video you’ll come to understand the pillars of his work & how it is the collective understanding from MANY areas that support this approach to low back pain. This is the approach I use each and every day with my patients as many of you have seen. It works. Period.
.
If you’d like to learn more, check out

Notice the shift in Heather's deadlift set up which causes her to pull off balance and twist slightly during this lift. I started this days assessment by looking at her hip mobility on both sides. Her right side checked out well, however when I brought her leg up to her chest on the left side she noticed a little pinching pain in the front of the hip joint that worsened as I brought the knee across her body. 📝
.
This test showed she was dealing with a hip impingement, where the femur was running into the front side of the hip socket and creating a pinching pain in the front of the hip. This means her unbalanced set up and pull was because she was shifting and twisting away from the impingement. 📝
.
To make some more room for the femur within the hip socket we worked on some banded joint mobilizations pulling laterally on the hip. I had her lean forward for a few seconds while pushing the hip into the prior restriction before coming out, driving the knee wide and squeezing her lateral glutes for 10 reps total. We then attempted the hip airplane unassisted.✅
.
After 1 week of using these exercises you can see a huge improvement in her bottom set position, here it is compared to her prior week. This allowed her to then perform a more balanced and optimal pull.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @heathaaarey for putting in the hard work to fix these movement issues and to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body in todays post🙏🏼

Squatting all comes down to balance. For some people the knees will HAVE to move forward past the toes in order to descend to a great depth and maintain balance. For others, the knees wont pass the knees, and that's okay too as long as they are staying balanced. When dealing with knee pain, it is often a good idea to limit the amount of knee-over-toe translation as pushing this forward motion can many times create more pain. Doing so can allow us to take stress of the symptomatic joint and address the cause of pain (by looking at mobility problems at the hips/ankles and/or stability issues). Context matters. 
.

node.text:
Early in my career as a physical therapist, it was common to prescribe certain stretches (like pulling your knees to your chest while lying on your back) as an exercise for many with low back pain. At the time this exercise made sense. Those who had difficulty standing for long periods or lying flat on their back often felt better when in a flexed position. Many who complained of feeling stiff and painful in their low back had instant relief of their symptoms after performing a few of these stretches.🤔
.
However, I realized (after reading and studying from Dr. Stuart McGill @backfitpro) that this relief is only a temporary relief for most. When you stretch your low back, you are stimulating the stretch receptors deep inside the muscles that give the perception of pain relief and the feeling of less stiffness.🤯
.
In fact, most of the muscle pain and stiffness you may feel in your back is consequence of a chemical reaction called inflammation that occurs from the real injury often located deeper in the spine (disc bulge, facet irritation, etc). The underlying injury is what causes the secondary contraction or spasm of the surrounding muscles and pain.🤯
.
Unlike other stretches for the low back that can place unwanted stresses on the spine, the cat-camel exercise emphases mobility in a very spine-friendly low load manner. If you'd like to learn more about what I do AFTER the cat-camel, check out the full rest of this video on my YouTube "Quick Tips for Low Back Tweaks.”📲
.
If you’re also dealing with low back pain, it is key to find out your exact movement triggers for pain (as there is no one size fits all treatment). To learn the tests I use to determine your movement diagnosis - check out my blog “how to screen your low back pain” on squatuniversity.com📲
.

There's nothing wrong or bad with planks. However, we must understand them. They are a static (no movement) exercise. For some they're a great starting point. But for others, we can take our core stability work one step further and make it more "movement specific" to lifting by adding in some dynamic work to the arms with the stir the pot variation. When you are lifting weights we want to create sufficent core stability while the arms or legs are moving. This variation allows our assistant work to mimic the movements we perform in the gym just a little more. 
.

Want to know if your shoes are really too narrow for you? Try the shoe liner test I learned from Dr. Ray McClanahan of @correcttoes. This clip is from my most recent YouTube video that just dropped a few hours ago in which I showcase WHY many of our shoes are so bad for our feet and also 4 different types of barefoot shoes I like that can help you restore your natural foot shape.
.
WHY DOES THIS MATTER? Modern shoes cram our feet into an unnatural position which limits our foot from functioning optimally. This hinders foot stability and therefore our full potential when lifting! It also increases risk of foot deformities like bunions and hammer toes, and injuries like plantar fasciitis. The good thing is we can reverse a lot of these problems and regain better stability by adopting better shoes! 
.
Shout out to @myfootfunction for the graphic used in today's post and @ksonthana for letting me use the foot print from his little baby boy!

node.text:
Taking this approach & trying to make every single lift look amazing (from my lightest warm up on up) has made a huge difference in my own training. 
.
The why: When you try to make your warm up sets look amazing, You reinforce the ideal technique through the brain body connection called a motor pattern. Over time this allows you to handle more and more weight with better technique – maximizing your potential and decreasing risk of injury for when you’re truly testing your limits. If you “take it easy” on lighter lifts, because you don’t think they’re important, you miss out on strengthening this motor pattern to its optimal potential. 
.
Takeaway: You should approach the barbell the exact same EVERY single time.
.

Let’s talk about when you would use these two joint mobilizations. Let’s say you have a pinching pain in the front of your hip when in a deep squat or one toe that constantly turns to the side – the lateral joint mob in an all 4’s position with your foot to the side can be helpful to improve hip internal rotation mobility. Now if you need more hip extension with your lifting – that’s when you use the anterior hip mob, squeezing your glute and leaning forward slightly to assist with the natural motion of the hip. 
.
To learn more about hip mobility, be sure to check out my YouTube video “How to Improve Hip Mobility.”📲
.

node.text:
During a deadlift, your body moves from a position of hip flexion in the set up and performs the motion of hip extension as you stand.📝
.
In order to produce efficient pulling technique and perform optimally your body must equally produce strength and force from in the posterior chain (glutes and hamstrings). If however, you develop an imbalance where one side is not firing as strong as the other, it can create technique problems like a hip shift (something @dinolarsson here was dealing with for a few months)❌
.
One of my favorite warm ups prior to deadlifting for this reason is a simple bridge with a hold. You can do it a few different ways. So  me like to drive the heels into the ground with the cue to “squeeze the glutes.” For others, this may create some hamstring cramping. If this is you driving the toes into the ground and using the cue “push the floor away” will turn the quads on slightly, in turn this turns off your hamstring due to a process called reciprocal inhibition. Therefore the only thing left to extend the hip is, you guessed it, the glutes.🤯
.
After performing sets of 15 reps (5-10 second holds) over a few days, Dino was able to fix his movement problem and deadlift with a much more efficient balanced technique, no longer shifting to the left.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @dinolarsson for putting in the hard work to fix this problem & to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body🙏🏼

This is a novel exercise to help enhance shoulder stability when lifting overhead - something I first learned from @benlustigphysiotherapy. I’ve used it many times in the past half year with patients of mine recovering from shoulder pain who need more stability when lifting overhead and have seen tremendous improvements. 
.
When to use: be sure to try the test I showed in this video first!!!! If you’re weak - then try & retest to see if this is helpful for you. Remember, “corrective exercises” are only helpful if used in the right situation. Never do an exercise just because it looks cool on social media.😉
.
Shout out to @benlustigphysiotherapy for sharing this exercise with me & @edpilgrimdpt for being my model athlete today. Also shout out to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body & @olychad for his lifting demos.

node.text:
An unfortunate conversation I have with many patients dealing with lower body injuries. The squat is a non-negotiable movement for life. While we may need to take a step back from heavy loaded squats for a short time while we rebuild, we NEED to eventually return to slow progressive loading in order to gain capacity for LIFE. This is why I’m such a big proponent for every physical therapy clinic having kettlebells & a barbell/squat rack. Many see these as tools only to enhance performance and forget that the squat is a MOVEMENT ever before it’s an exercise. Training the squat pattern in a progressive manner is how we gain strength & capacity to navigate life. 
.
If you had a doctor that took a different route & helped you get back to lifting - tag them in the comments & say thanks. Let’s shout out the practitioners doing things the right way!

A helpful squat warm up complex to optimize a controlled bottom position and balanced ascent where the hips and chest rise together is the 1 and ½ squat sequence. With 30-35% sit down into your deepest bottom position for a second before performing a small half ascent and hold for a few seconds. Then sink back down. During the ascent feel for your body staying balanced across your entire foot – not too much in the heel or the toes. Try three reps before reracking and continuing your normal warm ups. 
.
Shout out to @mirabai_chanu for being my athlete model for today’s post!

Many problems that happen during the movement of the deadlift occur because of improper set up. When you create sufficient stability & lock your lats down ever before the bar is moved from the ground, you set the stage for a better quality and stronger lift! 
.
One of the most common faults is seeing the back move uncontrollably during the pull. If this is you, take notes here and watch some videos of @eddycoan on YouTube - he has excellent teachings for how to set up to limit this “energy leak.”
.

Why perform a deadlift like this? The most simple answer is it helps engage the lats and lock the back into a good position. You see when the band attempts to pull the bar forward, the body has to react to maintain optimal form. In order to keep the bar from pull away from the body, the lats have to sufficiently engage. These are the powerful V shaped muscles on your back that help extend the shoulders to keep the bar close and stiffen the trunk for optimal deadlifting technique. 
.
The scientific term for this type of training is called RNT or reactive neuromuscular training.
.
Shout out to @joesullivan_aod for being my athlete model today and also to @briannyt for introducing these into his training!
